Regressive drunken leaders will be required to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of Interior would, after three drunk driving violations, require the installation of a vehicle that would prevent the start of the vehicle if the driver is drunk or does not blow into the structure.
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor's Office, according to which the pilot project will take one year.
Since the project is intended to return to the market, the driver will also have to participate in a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the General Public Prosecutor’s Office, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Car Safety (FITSA) are involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of the carmen arrested repeatedly because of drunken driving are re-caring.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the level of alcohol in the air. If it is larger than permitted, or if the driver did not even blow into the device, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of an instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the instigator.
A relevant study in the USA in 2007 has shown that vehicles equipped with such instruments may reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved by this rule every year.
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming a criminal offense,
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce, since the implementation of the legal reform is carried out in the ordinary way, while the necessary criminal reform requires a basic amendment of the law.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although in experimental mode some industrial and public vehicles have already been installed.
The House tomorrow votes on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Labour Party, which calls for the installation of the system in school buses - a French sample.
