Hepatitis: When should we contact a doctor?
Some half a billion people in the world are suffering from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, the leading causes of death are referred to chronic liver disease.
Hundreds of people with domestic hepatitis can be treated, but only seven thousand, which is why they don't know that they're infected.
The hepatitis name is a collector name of infected liver injuries caused by various viruses.
They have a lot of similarities, liver inflammation and yellowishness, but their pathogens and causing diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the feed channel (e.g. infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (such as vaginal fluids, swallowing).
Passengers are certainly worth protecting against the A and B virus, and there is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis occur two to three weeks after eating infected food, generally unwell, weakness, abdominal pain, nausea.
Then the yellowness on the skin and eye whites, the faeces are clear, the urine becomes dark, healing can take two or three weeks.
A million people worldwide die in the more severe type of disease, liver cancer caused by hepatitis B and liver cortex.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected is given medications.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to liver swollenness and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know about the disease because the pathogen is killing the liver cells underneath, and in many cases the first symptoms will occur only in 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
In three groups, there is much more of this disease than average: people who had transplanted blood, drug users and tattoos before 1991.
The number of infected chronic hepatitis C viruses in the world is currently available to 200 million.
As the disease can be demonstrated by a routine laboratory test, contact your home doctor if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
By recognising the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, so the infectivity will be eliminated and cancer can be prevented.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organised in 2004 by patient-representing organisations worldwide.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, the causes of development and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
